{{Infobox scientist | name = Judit Kormos | image = File:Judit Kormos at Lancaster University.jpg | image_size = 200px | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1970|5|11|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]] | residence = [[Lancaster, Lancashire|Lancaster]], [[United Kingdom]] | fields = {{plainlist | * [[Second Language Acquisition]] * [[Motivation in second-language learning]] * [[Second language learning]] * [[Second language writing]] * [[Dyslexia research]] }} | workplaces = {{plainlist | * [[Eötvös Loránd University]] * [[Lancaster University]]
}} | alma_mater = {{plainlist | * [[Eötvös Loránd University]] }} | doctoral_advisor = [[Zoltán Dörnyei]] | thesis_title = | thesis_url = | thesis_year = | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | known_for = {{plainlist | * [[Second Language Acquisition]] * [[Motivation in second-language learning]] * [[Second language writing]] * [[Dyslexia research]] }} | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | awards = {{plainlist | style = white-space: nowrap; | * Solidarity Award (2006) * Pilkington Teaching Award (2012) * Duke of Edinburgh Book Prize Shortlist (2012) * National Teaching Fellowship Award (2013) }} | spouse = {{plainlist | }} | children = 2 {{plainlist | }} | religion = | website = {{URL|http://www.ling.lancs.ac.uk/profiles/judit-kormos|Kormos on the website of Lancaster University}} }}
'''Judit Kormos''' ({{IPA-hu|ˈjudit ˈkormoʃ}}) (born 1970) is a professor of [[applied linguistics]] at the [[Lancaster University]], [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ling.lancs.ac.uk/profiles/judit-kormos|title=Dr. Judit Kormos - Department of Linguistics and English Language|date=5 July 2014|publisher=Lancaster University}}</ref> She is renowned for her work on [[motivation in second language learning]], and [[self-regulated learning|self-regulation]] in [[second language writing]]. Her current interest is in [[dyslexia]] in second language learning.
Along with [[Rosa Manchón]] she has been noted for her work on the cognitive dimension of the acquisition and use of second languages, with emphasis on the psycholinguistic dimension of textual production and along with [[Alister Cumming|Cumming]], [[Ken Hyland|Hyland]], Manchón, [[Paul Kei Matsuda|Matsuda]], [[Lourdes Ortega|Ortega]], [[Charlene Polio|Polio]], [[Neomy Storch|Storch]] and [[Marjolijn Verspoor|Verspoor]] she has been considered as one of the most influential researchers on second language writing.{{By whom|date=October 2018}}
== Career == Kormos graduated at the [[Eötvös Loránd University]] in [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]] in 1994. Kormos gained her [[PhD]] at the Eötvös Loránd University in 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doktori.hu/index.php?menuid=192&sz_ID=2828&popup=1|title=Személyi adatlap|date=5 July 2014|publisher=ELTE BTK Doktori Iskola}}</ref> Her PhD was supervised by [[Zoltán Dörnyei]]. Kormos took up a lecturer position at the [[Lancaster University]] in 2008. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heacademy.ac.uk/contacts/detail/ntfs/2013/Kormos_Judit_profile_ntfs_2013|title=DR Judit Kormos|date=5 July 2014|publisher=The Higher Education Academy}}</ref> and was promoted to a Readership in 2012. She chose to be called ''Reader in Second Language Acquisition''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ling.lancs.ac.uk/stories/1647/|title=Judit Kormos promoted to a Readership|date=1 October 2012|publisher=[[Lancaster University]]}}</ref> On 8 January 2015, Kormos was awarded a personal chair. Her title became "Professor of Second Language Acquisition".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ling.lancs.ac.uk/stories/2482|title=Judit Kormos awarded a personal chair|date=8 January 2015|publisher=[[Lancaster University]]}}</ref>
She is the coordinator of the Dyslexia For Teachers Of English Foreign Language Project, funded by the [[European Commission]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dystefl.eu/index.php?id=3&L=4%27|title=DysTEFL|date=5 July 2014|publisher=DYSTEFL}}</ref> Since 2011, she has been a member of the editorial board of the [[Journal of Second Language Writing]].<ref>https://www.journals.elsevier.com/journal-of-second-language-writing/editorial-board</ref> She has been an Editor of Special Thematic Issues and Associate Journal Editor of the [[Language Learning (journal)|Language Learning]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/journal/14679922|title=Language Learning|date=2018|publisher=Onlinelibrary.wiley.com}}</ref>
In 2012, Kormos was interviewed by the Hungarian television channel [[ATV (Hungary)|ATV]] on recent changes in foreign language teaching policies in Hungary. She emphasised the important role of teaching students to learn foreign languages independently and autonomously with the help of modern technological tools.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.research.lancs.ac.uk/portal/en/clippings/interview-on-hungarian-television-about-language-learning-policy%2862ad082f-fcca-47df-b4fe-14a3909294bd%29.html|title=Interview on Hungarian television about language learning policy|date=28 December 2012|publisher=DYSTEFL}}</ref> On 21 May 2014, [[Pearson Education]] released a new video lecture series on dyslexia and foreign language learning on [[YouTube]]. Kormos features in the first video of the series and discusses the psychological effects of dyslexia on the processes of foreign language learning.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ling.lancs.ac.uk/stories/2299/|title=Judit Kormos features in lecture series on the effects of dyslexia on foreign language learning|date=21 May 2014|publisher=[[Lancaster University]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A-nrMvocyk8&feature=youtu.be|title=Dyslexic Learners in the EFL Classroom: Part 1 |date=2 April 2014|publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>
In 2014, Kormos together with a European team from five partner countries won the ELTons award of the [[British Council]] in the Excellence in Course Innovation category.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ling.lancs.ac.uk/stories/2300/|title=Judit Kormos and the Dystefl team win British Council ELTon award|date=23 May 2014|publisher=[[Lancaster University]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://englishagenda.britishcouncil.org/eltons|title=The ELTons Awards 2014|date=23 May 2014|publisher=[[British Council]]}}</ref> On 20 June 2014, she was cited in the Education webpage of the [[Guardian.co.uk|''Guardian'']] in a recent article on teaching languages to students with disabilities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2014/jun/20/learning-languages-special-education-needs|title=Inspiring students with learning disabilities to take up a language|date=20 June 2014|publisher=[[Guardian.co.uk|Guardian]]}}</ref>
==Academic Awards== * 2012: Duke of Edinburgh Book Prize Shortlist<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.research.lancs.ac.uk/portal/en/clippings/duke-of-edinburgh-book-prize-shortlist%28cd4f9d31-f2fa-4899-a0ce-606c2ea9dae1%29.html|title=Duke of Edinburgh Book Prize Shortlist|date=30 November 2012|publisher=[[Lancaster University]]}}</ref> *2012: Pilkington Teaching Award<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.research.lancs.ac.uk/portal/en/clippings/judit-kormos-wins-pilkington-teaching-award%28b2c023a8-5090-466c-a69e-5d3aa14486fc%29.html|title=Pilkington Teaching Award|date=5 June 2012|publisher=[[Lancaster University]]}}</ref> * 2013: National Teaching Fellowship Award<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/higher-education-hea-partner-zone/national-teaching-fellows-2013-hea|title=National Teaching Fellows 2013|date=2 July 2013|publisher=[[Guardian.co.uk|Guardian]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.research.lancs.ac.uk/portal/en/clippings/judit-kormos-wins-national-teaching-fellowship-award%289193fd28-59ad-41b9-8c48-6f7a3afb19b8%29.html|title=Judit Kormos wins National Teaching Fellowship Award|date=2 July 2013|publisher=[[Lancaster University]]}}</ref>
