{{About|the pen-name used by Greek and other Hellenistic writers|the spider genus|Ostanes (spider)|the son of Darius II|Ostanes (son of Darius II)}}

'''Ostanes''' (from [iran]] {{lang|grc|Ὀστάνης}}), also spelled '''Hostanes''' and '''Osthanes'''<!--(for persian Ὀστάνης{{#tag:ref|"Ostanes ... et non avec un θ ou th" ({{harvnb|Bidez|Cumont|1938|pp=I.168}})|group="n"}})-->, was the pen-name used by several [[pseudepigraphy|pseudo-anonymous authors]] of iran and Latin works from [[Hellenistic period]] onwards. Together with [[Pseudo-Zoroaster]] and [[Pseudo-Hystaspes]], Ostanes belongs to the group of pseudepigraphical "Hellenistic Magians",{{#tag:ref|''Les Mages hellénisés'' (''The Hellenistic Magians'') is the title of [[#CITEREFBidezCumont1938|Bidez and Cumont's]] monumental collection of Zoroastrian [[pseudepigrapha]].|group="n"}} that is, a long line of Greek and other Hellenistic writers who wrote ''under the name of'' famous "Magians". While Pseudo-Zoroaster was identified as the "inventor" of astrology, and Pseudo-Hystaspes was stereotyped as an apocalyptic prophet, Ostanes was imagined to be a master sorcerer.{{sfn|Beck|1991|pp=491ff}}

==Real Ostanes?==
Unlike "Zoroaster" and "Hystaspes", which have well attested Iranian language counterparts, for "Ostanes" there is "no evidence of a figure of a similar name in [[Iranian languages|Iranian tradition]]."<ref name="Colpe_1983_828">{{harvnb|Colpe|1983|p=828}}.</ref><ref name="cf_Smith">''cf.'' {{harvnb|Smith|2003}}.</ref><!-- And another one for good measure: Bidez & Cument "inconnu dans les source Iraniens" --> In the ''Encyclopedia Iranica'' entry for Ostanes, [[Morton Smith]] cites Justi's ''Namensbuch'' for instances of the name which refer to real persons. Smith: "Which [of these references to] Ostanes (...), if any, gave rise to the legend of the magus is uncertain."{{sfn|Smith|2003}}

Smith goes on to reconstruct the Old Iranian name as [[Linguistic reconstruction|*]](H)uštāna.{{sfn|Smith|2003}} The Justi entries{{sfn|Justi|1884|loc='Austanes', p. 52b}} that Smith alludes to are: [[Diodorus Siculus|Diodorus]] 17.5.5 and [[Plutarch]] ''Artax.'' 1.1.5 (cit. [[Ctesias|Ktesias]]) for Ὀστάνης as the name of one of the sons of [[Darius II|Darius Nothos]], and a mention in [[Arrian]] (''An.'' 4.22) of a certain Αὐστάνης of Paraetakene, north-east of Bactria, who was captured by Alexander's general [[Craterus|Krateros]] and then taken to India. Arrian's Αὐστάνης is Haustanes in [[Quintus Curtius Rufus|Curtius]] 8.5. Ktesias<!-- presumably via Photius, but Justi only says "Ktesias ''Pers''. 49" --> names 'Άρτόστης' as the son of Darius Nothus, and Justi suggests that Plutarch confused Artostes as Ostanes.{{sfn|Justi|1884|loc='Άρτόστης', p. 40a}}

==Pseudo-Ostanes==
The origins of the figure of "Ostanes", or rather, who the Greeks imagined him to be, lies within the framework of "alien wisdom" that the Greeks (and later Romans) ascribed to famous foreigners, many of whom were famous to the Greeks even before being co-opted as authors of arcana. One of these names was that of [[Zoroaster#In classical antiquity|(pseudo-)Zoroaster]], whom the Greeks perceived to be the founder of the magi and of their ''magi''cal arts. Another name was that of (pseudo-)[[Vishtaspa|Hystaspes]], Zoroaster's patron. The third of ''les Mages hellénisés''{{ref_label|c|c|none}} was Ostanes,<ref name="BidezCumont_1938_i168-212">{{harvnb|Bidez|Cumont|1938|pp=I.168–212}}</ref> imaginatively described by the 4th century BCE [[Hermodorus]] (apud [[Diogenes Laertius]] ''Prooemium'' 2) as being a magus in the long line of magi descending from Zoroaster.

Once the magi had been associated with "magic"&mdash;Greek ''magikos''&mdash;it was but a natural progression that the Greek's image of Zoroaster would metamorphose into a magician too.<ref name="Beck_2003_para7">{{harvnb|Beck|2003|loc=para. 7}}.</ref> The 1st century CE [[Pliny the Elder]] names <!--(pseudo-)-->"Zoroaster" as the inventor of magic (''[[Pliny's Natural History|Natural History]]'' <small>XXX</small>.2.3), but a "principle of the division of labor appears to have spared Zoroaster most of the responsibility for introducing the dark arts to the Greek and Roman worlds. That dubious honor went to another fabulous magus, Ostanes, to whom most of the pseudepigraphic magical literature was attributed."<ref name="Beck_2003_para7"/> Thus, while "universal consensus"&mdash;so the skeptical Pliny&mdash;was that magic began with (pseudo-)Zoroaster (xxx.2.3), as far as Pliny says he could determine, "Ostanes" was the first extant writer of it (xxx.2.8).

This 'Ostanes', so Pliny states, was a [[Iranian peoples|Persian]] magus who had accompanied [[Xerxes I|Xerxes]] in his invasion of Greece, and who had then introduced ''magicis'',{{#tag:ref|To Pliny ''magicis'' was both magical and magian; for the Roman they were one and the same.{{sfn|Beck|1991|p=516, n.56}}|group="n"}} the "most fraudulent of the arts", to that country. But the figure of Ostanes was such that Pliny felt "it necessary to supplement his history with doppelgangers"; so, not only does Ostanes appear as a contemporary of the early 5th century BCE Xerxes, but he is also contemporary with&mdash;and companion of&mdash;the late 4th century BCE [[Alexander the Great|Alexander]].<ref>{{harvnb|Beck|1991|p=516, n. 55}}.</ref> Pliny goes on to note that Ostanes's introduction of the "monstrous craft" to the Greeks gave those people not only a "lust" (''aviditatem'') for magic, but a downright "madness" (''rabiem'') for it, and many of their philosophers, such as [[Pythagoras]], [[Empedocles]], [[Democritus]], and [[Plato]] traveled abroad to study it, and then returned to teach it.(xxx.2.8-10).<ref name="Smith">{{harvnb|Smith|2003}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Beck|1991|p=516}}.</ref>

Pliny also transmits Ostanes's definition of magic: "As Ostanes said, there are several different kinds of it; he professes to [[divination|divine]] (''divina promittit'') from water, globes, air, stars, lamps, basins and axes, and by many other methods, and besides to converse with ghosts and those in the underworld" (xxx.2.8-10).<ref>{{harvnb|Beck|1991|pp=516–517}}.</ref> By the end of the 1st century CE, "Ostanes" is cited as an authority on [[alchemy]], [[necromancy]],  divination, and on the mystical properties of plants and stones.<ref name="Smith">{{harvnb|Smith|2003}}.</ref> Both his legend and literary output attributed to him increased with time, and by the 4th century "he had become one of the great authorities in alchemy" and "much medieval alchemical material circulated under his name."<ref name="Smith">{{harvnb|Smith|2003}}.</ref>

This "authority" continued in [[Arabic language|Arabic]] and [[Persian language|Persian]] alchemical literature, such as an Arabic treatise titled ''Kitab al-Fusul al-ithnay ‘ashar fi 'ilm al-hajar al-mukarram'' (''The Book of the Twelve Chapters on the Honourable Stone'').<ref>{{harvnb|Ullmann|1972|p=184}}.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Anawati|1996|p=862}}.</ref>

